{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"daf4126d-3a38-41d8-8bda-f2eff263e492","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. The lifecycle is now handled on the **`Window`** class. You create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding methods:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (Window) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n        // Initialization logic (was OnStart)\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n        // Background logic (was OnSleep)\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n        // Foreground logic (was OnResume)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    return new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n}\n```\n\nYou also have `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, and `OnDestroying()` for finer-grained control. Alternatively, you can use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for platform-specific lifecycle hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fdfe4d5e-e126-477c-9dbd-b4980505480f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed — you use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events via `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and hook into `Window` events.\n\nActually, let me be more precise:\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has those virtual methods. Instead, you handle lifecycle through `Window` events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, and `Resumed` by overriding `CreateWindow` in your `App` class, or you can use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` for platform-specific handling. Window class has these overridable methods: `OnCreated()`, `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, `OnStopped()`, `OnResumed()`, and `OnDestroying()`. So the lifecycle mapping from the older framework is `OnStart` maps to `Window.OnCreated()`, `OnSleep` maps to `Window.OnStopped()`, and `OnResume` maps to `Window.OnResumed()`.","outputTokens":982,"requestId":"A854:1D44F2:68DD8F:7917C8:69FBE31A"},"id":"079f6204-cfbc-44c5-8afe-0f7f80147888","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:56:12.167Z","parentId":"3e5e9f63-3587-427e-a1b0-04d5671ba8b0"}
